The answer is &#39;learn how to reference child controls&#39;, then call methods on the child control. 


This page gives 3 good ideas on how to facilitate inter-component communication beyond the @input() method. None really addressed my situation... but they are 3 good ideas that work.
https://medium.com/@mirokoczka/3-ways-to-communicate-between-angular-components-a1e3f3304ecb

I realized there must be a way to reference other components directly in angular. I found this article about @ViewComponent
https://alligator.io/angular/viewchild-access-component/


This page is a very good article on using @ViewComponent and works through 3 different examples. Very illustrative. Nice work.
https://www.concretepage.com/angular-2/angular-2-viewchild-example


Ultimately the answer is to change the listcomponent so that it has a reference to the child detailcomponent. This is done using the @ViewComponent decorator as follows 



    export class propertyAnalysisListComponent implements OnInit, AfterViewInit{
    
      listFormGroup: FormGroup; 
      paVers: propertyAnalysisVersion[];
      selectedpaVer: propertyAnalysisVersion;
    
      @ViewChild(propertyAnalysisDetailComponent)
      private myDetail: propertyAnalysisDetailComponent;
      

It&#39;s important to note (took me some fumbling to realize) that the final two lines are in fact 1 line. 

The  declaration/type is being decorated w/ the @ViewChild. 
 
The detail component is now addressable in the tr.click method of the documentList component


      onRowClicked(evt: MouseEvent, paVer: propertyAnalysisVersion) {
        //alert(paVer.versionName);
        this.selectedpaVer = paVer;
        this.myDetail.patchControls(paVer);  //set control values w/ the new data object
      }
    }

 
hope this helps someone else.

